AFI L.A. INTERNATIONAL FESTIVAL: CAPSULE REVIEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By -- MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following are capsule reviews of today's screenings in the American Film 
Institute Los Angeles International Film Festival at the Cineplex Odeon Century 
Plaza Cinemas: 
</P>
<P>
'Fable of the Beautiful Pigeon Fancier' 
</P>
<P>
Brazil, 1988, 103 minutes 
</P>
<P>
7:15 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Just as in "Letters From the Park," Gabriel Garcia Marquez based this 
screenplay on a two-page fragment from "Love in the Time of Cholera"; it's a 
sensuous, cruel love story about a compulsive seducer with waxed mustache whose 
obsessive romanticism brings on catastrophe. Cinema Novo mainstay Ruy Guerra 
("Erendira") has turned into a master of gorgeous surfaces, but he never loses 
sight of the devastating social satire Marquez has secreted within his 
Scheherazade-style storytelling and jeweled metaphors. RECOMMENDED. -- MICHAEL 
WILMINGTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
