NATION; 
</P>
<P>
POLL BACKS STRICT IMMIGRATION CURBS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A poll of 800 California voters shows widespread support for stricter measures 
to curb illegal immigration across the U.S.-Mexican border, a group that 
commissioned the survey said today. 
</P>
<P>
Sixty-nine percent of Californians surveyed said they favored strict limits on 
the number of legal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 60% supported a government plan to build a four-mile 
drainage ditch along the border in San Diego County to thwart Mexican motorists 
who speed across the desert to enter the country illegally. 
</P>
<P>
The Federation for American Immigration Reform commissioned the poll, which was 
conducted April 6-9 by Tarrance &amp; Associates of Houston. 
</P>
